## 10. Design Rationale

**Why a pre-compiled workspace?** The dominant cost in repeat inference (e.g., UQ with many evidence samples) is the message passing, not index computation. By pre-computing all gather/scatter index maps at construction time ([build_message_schedule](file:///Users/akrambatikh/Documents/projects/Libraries/BN%20C++/bncore/src/workspace.cpp#138-321)), each [calibrate()](file:///Users/akrambatikh/Documents/projects/Libraries/BN%20C++/bncore/src/workspace.cpp#511-927) call reduces to flat-array reads and multiply-accumulate loops with no runtime stride arithmetic, no temporary [Factor](file:///Users/akrambatikh/Documents/projects/Libraries/BN%20C++/bncore/include/bncore/factors/factor.hpp#8-34) allocations, and no scope set-intersection.

**Why uint32_t index maps instead of on-the-fly stride arithmetic?** Address computation for multi-dimensional tensor indexing requires division and modulo operations. These are replaced by a single array dereference per product index, improving CPU cache utilization and enabling auto-vectorization of the inner loops.

**Why lazy copy-on-write?** In the UQ use case, evidence is sparse: only a few variables are observed per sample. Most cliques are not touched by evidence. The COW mechanism avoids re-propagating messages through the entire tree for each new evidence set; only the subtrees rooted at evidence-adjacent cliques are recomputed.

**Why `uint8_t` dirty flags instead of `vector<bool>`?** `vector<bool>` is bit-packed and not byte-addressable. `memset` on a `uint8_t` vector clears all $C$ flags in a single cache-line-efficient store. Individual flag reads and writes are single-byte operations, eliminating bit-masking overhead in the hot loop bodies.

**Why chunk-level parallelism instead of intra-clique SIMD?** Each [calibrate()](file:///Users/akrambatikh/Documents/projects/Libraries/BN%20C++/bncore/src/workspace.cpp#511-927) call is not parallelizable internally without synchronization (the collect and distribute passes are inherently sequential along the tree). Parallelism is achieved by running independent [BatchWorkspace](file:///Users/akrambatikh/Documents/projects/Libraries/BN%20C++/bncore/include/bncore/inference/workspace.hpp#57-58) instances on different evidence rows simultaneously via `std::async`, one workspace per thread, with no shared mutable state.

**Why normalize at query time, not during propagation?** Normalizing calibrated potentials during propagation would require an additional pass and arithmetic. Since the query returns a marginal over a single variable, normalization is performed cheaply on the output slice (at most a few dozen states) at extraction time. This avoids modifying the calibrated potentials, which are shared across multiple query calls.

**Why force chunk_size = 1 for the hotpath dispatch?** The workspace's internal message-passing kernels and gather maps are designed for a single evidence row (B=1). Introducing a native batched workspace (B>1 within [calibrate](file:///Users/akrambatikh/Documents/projects/Libraries/BN%20C++/bncore/src/workspace.cpp#511-927)) would require separate buffer layouts, additional index arithmetic, and more complex COW logic. The engine achieves multi-sample throughput by dispatching multiple B=1 workspaces in parallel across threads, reusing the proven single-row code path without modification.
